<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>CONSULTATION RESPONSE</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">NASUWT – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:21.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT’s submission sets out the Union’s views on the key issues identified by the Bill Committee. This evidence draws on the experiences </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">and views of the Union’s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> serving teachers and school leaders.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:21.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT is the largest teachers’ union in the UK, with over 280,000 serving teacher and school leader members.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GENERAL COMMENTS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:21.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT is extremely concerned about the impact that the Deregulation Bill could have upon the legislative and democratic framework of the United Kingdom. Key clauses could centralise enormous power into the hands of ministers with little regard for the checks and balances within the apparatus of the state. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:21.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The nature and scale of the Bill is huge and there are considerable risks therefore that the evidence may not be produced for single clauses that would in a Bill of smaller scope and less scrutiny may therefore be given to all aspects of the Bill. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:21.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">As a result of these serious concerns, the Union would welcome the opportunity to give oral evidence and further more substantial written evidence to the Bill Committee.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:21.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT is concerned that the aspects of the Deregulation Bill constitute a further attack on schools/colleges, pupils and teachers by the Coalition Government. The Union’s submission highlights particular concerns in respect of the Coalition Government’s programme for deregulation in education.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:21.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Coalition Government claims that the Deregulation Bill will reduce needless bureaucracy for businesses but, as with much of its so-called reduction of red tape, much is predicated on privileging businesses to the detriment of workers or consumers.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:21.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Coalition Government’s attempts to reduce the burdens for employers in the instances cited will, in many cases, create further risks and turbulence for employees and in the case of schools/colleges, for parents, children and young people.  Deregulation does not, in and of itself, indicate the reduction or removal of bureaucracy.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:21.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT is clear that no-one wishes to be burdened with unnecessary regulations but that in the case of the Deregulation Bill, extensive and far-reaching changes are proposed by the Coalition Government without any evidential basis being provided of the need for such changes or of the impact of such changes. In many cases, the proposals are in direct opposition to the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">weight of national and international evidence on good practice.  The Committee must question why these changes are needed in this Bill at this time, and assess what the impact will be on businesses, consumers, workers and children and young people.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Throughout this response, there are a number of concerns about many aspects of the Bill and its impact. There are human rights and equalities concerns about the impact of changes regarding tribunals and about changes related to discipline in schools and the determination of school terms, for example, that do not seem to be considered fully. The NASUWT urges the Committee to insist on a comprehensive and rigorous equality impact assessment of all provisions in the draft Bill, and to ensure that the Coalition Government demonstrates full compliance with the public sector duty under the Equality Act 2010.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The particular areas relating to the provision of education are in Schedules 13 and 14, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">as</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> asked by the Committee in question 7 </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">iv</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. These two schedules include a range of measures that claim to reduce burdens on schools. There is no evidence that these measures are required by the generality of teachers, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">headteachers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, school governors, local authorities or parents/carers in maintained schools. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The remainder of this response focuses on those aspects relating to education and schools or general concerns the NASUWT has with aspects of the Bill and the lack of evidence provided for it </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">as</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> asked by the Committee in question 3. Due to the sheer scale of the changes proposed, the NASUWT will be provided with further and more detailed evidence on each of the aspects covered within this submission.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">SPECIFIC COMMENTS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 3: English Apprenticeships: simplification</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The proposals set out the framework of the new system for apprenticeships based on the Richard Review of apprenticeships. The NASUWT had concerns about aspects of the Richard Review proposals and, more particularly, concerns about the Coalition Government’s attempts to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">marketise</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> qualifications and their general view of vocational qualifications. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Union believes that there is insufficient detail in the Bill to assess the potential impact of the proposed changes. Furthermore, a clear rationale needs to be provided as to why the proposed changes are necessary.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT believes that the wording as proposed in Clause 3 is unacceptably open-ended and poorly drafted, and would provide the Secretary of State for Education with a ‘blank cheque’ to make any further changes as he sees fit without appropriate reference to Parliament. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Union believes that any reform of qualifications should be conducted with the intention to develop a coherent qualifications offer for all 14-19 year </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">old learners, in which there is parity of esteem between ‘vocational’ and ‘academic’ learning pathways and consistency and coherence between the curriculum and qualifications framework. Unfortunately, the Department for Education’s (</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">) proposals for reform of vocational qualifications for 16-19 year olds would fragment further the qualification system by creating a divide between different forms of vocational qualifications and their relative status in the official tables of school and college performance. This is reflected in their attitudes to apprenticeships.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 33: Schools: reduction of burdens</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This clause of the Bill removes the requirement of local authorities or governing bodies to set annual targets relating to the educational performance of pupils in schools that are maintained by local authorities. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Although this may appear to remove a bureaucratic burden upon schools, the reality is that there is no evidence that this would help, as the accountability regime through national performance tables and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> inspections has such high stakes for schools that this measure would do little or nothing to reduce burdens. The Committee should note that the bureaucratic burdens for schools are principally related to the publication of national performance tables and the fall-out from </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> inspection. Until these issues are addressed it is unlikely that this measure could possibly have any positive effect on schools.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT is further concerned that this clause will lead to a further concentration of power in the hands of the Secretary of State as it will only be the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> alone who will be able to set such external targets. This is another example of the removal of local democratic accountability for schools and the taking away of the roles of local authorities in schools.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The clause removes a further link between local authorities and the schools that they maintain. Whilst this may have created burdens, it is arguable that such burdens were appropriate given the need to ensure local democratic accountability for education provision. The current arrangements also encourage dialogue between local authorities and local schools in the interests of securing sustainable school improvement and in assisting schools to meet national accountability imperatives. The draft Bill would result in local authorities being expected to secure high standards of education provision in their areas without being given appropriate levers of power. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 13: Regulation of qualification requirements for teaching staff and principals</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This section of the schedule effectively removes the requirement for teachers in further and higher education to have teaching qualifications. This change is part of a deliberate attack by the Coalition Government upon teachers and the whole nature of the teaching profession and follows a similar removal of the requirement for children and young people to be taught by qualified teachers. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The measure that is being removed was introduced to improve teaching and learning in colleges by ensuring that all teaching staff understood how to teach their subject. This will mean that teaching staff will be appointed who do not know how to teach, the primary purpose of their role. This whole measure flies in the face of substantial international evidence that demonstrates the importance of highly qualified teaching staff who understand not only their subjects but how to personalise education to meet an individual’s learning style</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and downgrades the profession in a way that would not be seen as acceptable in medicine or law.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The change will affect not only further and higher education students but also 14-16 year olds who are taught in a further education institution for all or some of their courses.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT condemns this proposal in the strongest terms.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 13:  Control of governance of designated institutions conducted by companies</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This section of the Schedule appears to suggest that the Secretary of State can no longer </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">direct companies forming articles of association. It is not clear why this is necessary and how, if this is implemented, the Secretary of State will be able to exercise due diligence in relation to the scrutiny of the policies and practices of such companies’ policies, including in respect of equality.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 14: Responsibility for discipline</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This section of the schedule removes the requirement for governing bodies to provide a statement of written principles for the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">headteacher</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to develop a behaviour policy. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Coalition Government has not provided any evidence as to why this change is necessary. The Committee should recognise that the existence of this measure provides the basis for governing bodies to exercise fully their role in relation to securing good behaviour in schools. All governing bodies agree behaviour policies as part of their key strategic role. It would be profoundly unhelpful if that duty on the governing body were to be removed or undermined in any way, as this measure risks doing. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.1pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT contends that governing bodies are engaged in the development and agreement of school behaviour policies, and, thus, de facto are engaged in the communication of behaviour policy principles which are central to the content of school behaviour policies. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This proposed change will give </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">headteachers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> more powers in relation to discipline and, in particular, remove the right of governors to scrutinise the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">behaviour policy, despite the fact that governing bodies would still remain publicly accountable if there were problems arising from the school’s behaviour policy. For example, in the case of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">a behaviour</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> policy which was found to be discriminatory, governing bodies could be held responsible, despite having no powers to develop the behaviour policy under question. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This proposed change excludes any notion of stakeholder or community engagement. In Sir Alan Steer’s report ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Learning Behaviours: Lessons Learned’</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> he stated </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">staff, pupils and parents are involved in the process [of reviewing behaviour policies] is extremely important and must be observed</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">’,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> yet this provision flies in the face of this recommendation by putting the responsibility squarely into one person’s hands.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Sir Alan further states ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Other changes in the 2006 Act included a widening of the duty on school governing bodies to consult on the overall principles of the school behaviour policy including, crucially, a duty to invite views not only from staff and parents but from all pupils. For disciplinary policies to be effective, it is clearly important for them to be properly understood and bought into by pupils. This development in the law consolidated existing good professional practice as well as serving to strengthen the legitimate disciplinary authority of schools.’</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Again, this provision undermines what this report saw as crucial to the operation of effective behaviour policies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT is extremely concerned about the impact that this could have upon pupils with protected characteristics under the Equalities Act 2010, particularly given the high levels of exclusions of some of those groups. The NASUWT believes that this is a retrograde step for dealing with bullying and prejudice and believes that this section should not be in such a Bill. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 14: Home-school agreements</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This section removes the need for schools to produce home-school agreements. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Home-school agreements were developed in order to ensure that schools worked closely with parents. In </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">a Department for Children, Schools and Families (DCSF) commissioned report, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘Behaviour and the role of home-school agreements</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">’,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Sir Alan Steer reported that ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Home-school agreements have an important role in ensuring that schools and parents work together to maintain high standards. When operated well, home-school agreements inform, promote pupil-parent-school engagement and bring together other school policies into a coherent whole.’</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The proposed change could send out a signal to schools that the building of positive parental relationships is not important. Any decision to remove this statutory </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">duty,</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> should be accompanied by a clear commitment to providing guidance to schools on securing good practice in the area of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">building relationships with parents and communities.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 14: Determining school terms</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This schedule deregulates the decision for determining school terms to individual school governing bodies. The Coalition Government has not given any evidence for doing this, largely because none is available, and has not given serious consideration of what the consequences of such a move could be upon schools, pupils, parents, school staff and the local community. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Coalition Government appears to have proposed this change on the basis of some spurious idea that the status quo has simply remained as it is, unquestioned since the pre-industrial era. In actuality, this issue has been the subject of review on numerous occasions. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In the early 1980s a national working party considered in detail the various options for change and decided to maintain the status quo.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In 2000 the Local Government Association (LGA) established a Commission, mainly consisting of parties supporting change, to report on the issue. Teacher unions were excluded from the deliberations. A report was published entitled </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> rhythms of schooling – a proposal to integrate the stages of learning, assessment and transfer with terms and holidays</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT submitted a response to the LGA Commission, stating that changing the status quo provided no clear educational benefit and there were far more important and pressing issues in education than disrupting the existing academic-year pattern.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">An agreement was reached and a statement was released in June 2004 to maintain the status quo and implement a standardised school year that consisted of three terms, encompassing uniform holiday dates consistent across local authorities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The agreement recognised that standardised term dates and school holidays provided consistency and predictability, which benefited pupils, teachers and parents. Part of the agreement was that the standard school-year model was to be followed robustly and policed by all local authorities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The following prerequisites were established in setting a uniform national pattern:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">start the school year on a September date as near as possible </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to 1 September;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">equalise teaching and learning blocks (roughly 2x7 and 4x6 weeks);</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">establish a two-week Spring break in early April, irrespective of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the incidence of the Easter bank holiday (where the break does not coincide with the bank holiday, a nationally agreed date should be implemented in order to be consistent across local authorities);</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">maintain a Summer holiday of at least six weeks, except where local authorities have historically had less than six but more than five weeks; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">identify</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and agree annually-designed holiday periods, including </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the Summer holiday.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">These factors continue to be the basis for determining school-year team dates in the vast majority of schools, including in voluntary-aided schools which have chosen to adopt the standardised pattern.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is clear from the basis of this evidence that the proposed change would create a system in which all schools within a local community have different term dates, thus creating additional problems for businesses, parents and communities. It would mean that parents who have pupils at more than one school would be additionally and adversely affected. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">For teachers, this could create even more problems if they have children in different schools as they will not even be able to make leave arrangements. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT is very concerned that the impact of this change will be felt most keenly on working mothers and that this could have a consequential impact upon their ability to stay in work or upon child-care costs. It is clear that there has not been an Equality Impact Assessment to examine this possibility.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> appears to believe that when making changes to term dates, schools will consult widely and will ensure that such changes take account of local needs. There is no evidence in support of the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">DfE’s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> assumption and no guarantee that consultation would take place on a meaningful basis.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is also clear that this could have an impact upon the nature and timing of examinations and other factors within the rhythm of the year.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">To make this change without a full consideration of the consequences, in order effectively to see whether some schools do innovate or to create a debate, is reckless and does not seem, judging from the reaction of stakeholder groups of teachers, parents, governors and councillors to be something that any of the groups believe was warranted.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="51" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> has attempted to suggest that a rationale for such a change is the need to observe religious holidays. This suggestion fails to recognise that there is already flexibility for schools within the system to vary up to five days in order to make such accommodations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT is also concerned about the economic effects of such a change, given the impact that this could have on the ability of businesses to plan effectively and the impact that this could have upon local infrastructure, such as public transport and policing.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT condemns this proposal and asks the Committee to reject this provision in the Bill. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 14: Staffing matters</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="54" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The schedule amends the requirement that schools must have regard to statutory guidance issued by the Secretary of State relating to the appointment, discipline, suspension and dismissal of staff. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="55" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Whilst this approach may be consistent with the Government’s aims of giving schools greater freedom over their affairs, the Union considers that the provision of such guidance is both necessary and effective.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="56" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The statutory guidance provided by the Secretary of State ensures that school leaders can ensure that the policies and procedures that are created for appointment, discipline, suspension and dismissal of staff are based on an authoritative framework that results in best practices.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="57" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT considers that the provision of statutory guidance is essential. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="58" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">These changes do not better serve the needs of schools; they will do nothing to support increased autonomy and do not empower governing bodies and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">headteachers</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. Rather they will leave schools without the clear guidance that they require so that they do not have to spend unnecessary time on creating their own procedures and policies from scratch, with only the regulations to guide them. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="59" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The failure by a governing body to properly take into account such guidance or advice could result in policies and procedures which are not fit for purpose and could then result in schools, academies and governing bodies facing employment tribunals for not correctly adhering to the procedures set out in the Regulations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="60" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT notes that the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> has only recently published guidance for managing staff employment in schools on 22 August 2013. The Union also notes that this is prefaced by the title ‘The essentials’. It states ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This section brings together all statutory guidance and key advice for schools. The statutory guidance reflects the current legal position and will be updated to reflect changes to legislation and government policy’</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="61" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The guidance itself states: ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The purpose of this document is to provide statutory guidance to maintained schools and local authorities on the </span><a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2009/2680/contents/made" target="_blank"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">School Staffing (England) Regulations 2009</span></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (“the 2009 Regulations”). The document is designed to help schools ensure they have a clear understanding of their statutory responsibilities regarding staff</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">employment matters. Where appropriate, it also gives some advice on, or pointers to, other acts and regulations relevant to the employment of staff in schools</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.’</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="62" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT believes that this is necessary and extremely helpful to schools and does not restrict them in any way and does not therefore see the need for such a change. Such a change downgrades further the status of the profession.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 14: Publication of reports</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="63" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.1pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This section removes the requirement for governing bodies to make available to the public, provide copies on request and ensure that parents receive copies of section 5 inspection reports, section 48 religious inspection reports, interim assessment reports and copies of reports relating to investigation of complaints about schools to the Chief Inspector. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="64" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Instead the schedule proposes that parents will receive notification of the overall outcome of section 5 and section 48 reports and will be able to request schools to provide a hard copy if they have no internet access.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="65" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Union understands that this new duty secures that every registered parent of a registered pupil at the school is informed of the overall assessment contained in the report of the quality of education provided in the school</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="66" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Union questions whether this proposal is necessary, how it will reduce burdens on schools and whether it will enhance communications and relationships between schools and parents.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 2: Removal of employment tribunals’ power to make wider recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="67" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This clause repeals section 124 of the Equality Act 2010. The NASUWT believes that this is an extremely concerning development.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="68" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Section 124 of the Equality Act 2010 gives employment tribunals the power to make an ‘appropriate recommendation’ where there has been a contravention of the Act. ‘Appropriate recommendation’ is defined at s124(3) as ‘a recommendation that within a specified period the respondent takes specified steps for the purpose of obviating or reducing the adverse effect of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">any matter to which the proceedings relate on the complainant (or) on any other person’.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="69" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Under equality legislation prior to the Equality Act, a tribunal could only make recommendations to the respondent that reduced the adverse effect of the discrimination on the claimant his or herself. The change was brought in because in 2008, a consultation carried out by the Government of the time highlighted the fact that 70% of employees who were involved in discrimination claims leave the respondent employer. This limited the tribunal’s power to make recommendations to try and ensure the same discrimination did not arise again. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="70" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It was for this reason that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s124(</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">3) was included in the Act; it meant that recommendations could be made for the benefit of the wider workforce. The types of recommendations that a tribunal can make include ensuring the respondent introduces an equal opportunities policy, re-trains staff and makes public its selection criteria used for staff transfer or promotion.     </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="71" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">An example of when the tribunal used this new power was the case of Stone v Ramsay Healthcare UK Operations Ltd ET/1400762/11. Here, the claimant resigned from her job after she had been the victim of pregnancy/maternity-related discrimination. Despite the claimant no longer working for the respondent, the tribunal ordered the employer to hire external consultants in order to implement a training programme on maternity for its managers and HR team, and to re-draft its equal opportunities policy.      </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="72" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In this instance, the consequences of removing these powers from the tribunal would potentially be that all of the employees at the respondent company would have to put up with managers who had not had appropriate training and an equal opportunities policy that was not fit for purpose. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="73" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Without the tribunal having the ability to make these recommendations for such changes, the status quo could have led to further incidents of discrimination towards members of staff. This would have resulted in more resignations and tribunal claims which would have had a negative impact on both the employees and the employer. It is for this reason that tribunal recommendations should not be seen as a punishment for employers but a way of improving their business.          </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="74" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT further notes that the TUC has reported that it knows of only four cases where such recommendations have been made by tribunals, thus clearly not creating a regulatory burden, and yet the Coalition Government still intends to make this change.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="75" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT opposes this proposal because it removes a power without evidence that it is a burden, and because the power currently sends a powerful signal to employers, and the wider legal and human resources community, advising business that discrimination is unacceptable, and ensuring, as in the example quoted, that discriminatory practice can be corrected. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clauses 50 - 57: Powers to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">disapply</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> legislation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="76" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This section refers to questions 10-16. The NASUWT is extremely concerned about how the power to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">disapply</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> legislation that is no longer considered of use may be used in the future. The clauses related to this do not appear to have appropriate or necessary checks and balances for such a far-reaching clause to be introduced or enough parameters set about how this could be determined.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="77" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Parliament should make decisions about which legislation does not apply and/or which appropriate processes should operate through the courts. Ministers or civil servants should not determine this alone. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clauses 58 – 61: Exercise of regulatory functions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="78" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">These clauses propose that regulators would have a duty to promote economic growth. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT concurs fully with the view of the TUC that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘these clauses are not only unnecessary but also potentially damaging and in some cases likely to compromise the independence of some regulatory bodies, for example, the HSE and the EHRC, both of which are required under EU legislation to operate at arm’s length from Government in the exercise of some of their statutory functions’.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="79" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:15.45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The NASUWT believes that the Coalition Government should remove these clauses and consider other ways of encouraging regulators to exercise their statutory functions. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">16 September 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">1</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> OECD (2012), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Preparing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> teachers and developing school leaders for the 21</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> century: Lessons from Around The World, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Paris</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, p11.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Sir Alan Steer (2009), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Learning Behaviours: Lessons Learned</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">’, DCSF, </span><a href="http://www.educationengland.org.uk/documents/pdfs/2009-steer-report-lessons-learned.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">http://www.educationengland.org.uk/documents/pdfs/2009-steer-report-lessons-learned.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Sir Alan Steer (2010), </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">‘Behaviour and the role of home-school agreements, DCSF</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">http://www.educationengland.org.uk/documents/pdfs/2010-steer-behaviour-home-school.pdf</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Department for Education,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/guidanceandadvice?page=1"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/guidanceandadvice?page=1</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Department for Education,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, </span><a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/guidanceandadvice/g00213619/managing-staff-employment-schools"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/guidanceandadvice/g00213619/managing-staff-employment-schools</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">TUC (2013), Draft </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Dergulation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Bill – TUC Response.</span></p></body></html>